0:00:00.880,0:00:05.920
A data set by itself is not capable of explaining 
the full reality behind the data set. A data set

0:00:05.920,0:00:10.560
about an event is only a part of what happens 
in reality and a lot of information and context

0:00:10.560,0:00:15.520
goes missing. There are many ways to create 
visualizations and one of them is collaboration

0:00:15.520,0:00:19.760
between domain experts and visualization 
designers. But the issue here is that domain

0:00:19.760,0:00:23.680
experts are very knowledgeable about their 
topic but oftentimes do not have the knowledge

0:00:23.680,0:00:28.320
about visualization design. On the other hand, 
visualization designers are very skilled in making

0:00:28.320,0:00:33.280
visualizations but do not have enough knowledge 
about the context behind the data. This lack of

0:00:33.280,0:00:37.760
understanding causes miscommunication between 
designers and domain experts. This evidence

0:00:37.760,0:00:41.440
can also be found in literature. The comments 
such as "designers inferences about data were

0:00:41.440,0:00:45.760
often inaccurate" and "anticipating all of the 
implications of scale and interaction for given

0:00:45.760,0:00:50.640
data sets remains challenging" indicate that it is 
easy to be misled and if this could be addressed

0:00:50.640,0:00:54.960
then it would help the visualization design 
process. To that end, we develop a system called

0:00:54.960,0:00:59.760
the data therapist. Data therapist aims to enhance 
the understanding of datasets for lay audience by

0:00:59.760,0:01:05.200
eliciting knowledge through annotations about the 
data from experts. We let experts make annotations

0:01:05.200,0:01:09.600
to the data that's data set through a mixture of 
interaction approach to question answering and

0:01:09.600,0:01:14.480
user-driven annotation for extracting knowledge 
from domain experts. Data therapist has three

0:01:14.480,0:01:19.760
ways to make annotations. First is annotating the 
overall data set. Second is annotating a specific

0:01:19.760,0:01:23.680
region of interest. And third is answering 
data therapist initiated questions about the

0:01:23.680,0:01:36.480
dataset. Here's the first method where the user 
can make annotations about the overall data set.

0:01:36.480,0:01:42.160
The second method is where users can set 
specific data instance and then add annotations.

0:01:42.160,0:01:46.400
You can also conduct simple analysis by referring 
to visualizations such as histogram and scatter

0:01:46.400,0:01:54.640
plots to identify the correlation and anomalies 
and choose items of the expert's interest.

0:01:54.640,0:01:59.680
The third method is where questions are provided 
and the user can add annotations by answering the

0:01:59.680,0:02:04.560
provided questions. These questions are composed 
of LLM generated questions where you see a grid

0:02:04.560,0:02:08.800
symbol and a set of predefined questions that 
aim to enrich the descriptions about the data

0:02:08.800,0:02:19.520
set. Once the answers are added, then the system 
verifies if the answer aligns with the question.

0:02:19.520,0:02:24.000
Finally, as an output, we provide a CSV 
file that show the list of all annotation

0:02:24.000,0:02:28.880
and set of questions and answers that the 
user has annotated. These annotations then

0:02:28.880,0:02:32.480
could be used to create reports that help 
the understanding of topics for the lay

0:02:32.480,0:02:38.400
audience or visualization designers. Here we 
present an example of how our system is used.

0:03:18.160,0:03:20.560
For an in-depth analysis of these annotations,

0:03:20.560,0:03:24.320
please refer to our paper. Our main 
focus is in understanding how their

0:03:24.320,0:03:29.520
the data therapists created annotations help 
bridge the knowledge gap between experts and

0:03:29.520,0:03:34.000
lay audience by comparing annotations 
with those from human guidance. Thank you.
